		},
		{
			"id": 1,
			"parent": 3,
			"text": "XPB is a subunit of the basal transcription factor TFIIH , which is also involved in nucleotide excision repair ( NER ) and potentially in cell cycle regulation . <S>",
			"relation": "BACKGROUND",
			"tag": "Background"
		},
		{
			"id": 2,
			"parent": 1,
			"text": "A frameshift mutation in the 3'-end of the XPB gene is responsible for a concurrence of two disorders : xeroderma pigmentosum ( XP ) and Cockayne 's syndrome ( CS ) . <S>",
			"relation": "ADDITION",
			"tag": "Background"
		},
		{
			"id": 3,
			"parent": 0,
			"text": "We have isolated TFIIH from cells derived from a patient ( XP11BE ) who carries this frameshift mutation ( TFIIHmut ) and from the mother of this patient ( TFIIHwt )",
			"relation": "ROOT",
			"tag": "Verification-Method"
		},
		{
			"id": 4,
			"parent": 3,
			"text": "to determine the biochemical consequences of the mutation . <S>",
			"relation": "ENABLEMENT",
			"tag": "Hypothesis-Objective"
		},
		{
			"id": 5,
			"parent": 6,
			"text": "Although identical in composition and stoichiometry to TFIIHwt ,",
			"relation": "COMPARISON",
			"tag": "Verification-Result"
		},
		{
			"id": 6,
			"parent": 3,
			"text": "TFIIHmut shows a reduced 3' --> 5' XPB helicase activity . <S>",
			"relation": "CAUSE-RESULT",
			"tag": "Verification-Result"
		},
		{
			"id": 7,
			"parent": 6,
			"text": "A decrease in helicase and DNA-dependent ATPase activities was also observed with the mutated recombinant XPB protein . <S>",
			"relation": "ADDITION",
			"tag": "Verification-Result"
		},
		{
			"id": 8,
			"parent": 6,
			"text": "The XPB mutation causes a severe NER defect . <S>",
			"relation": "ADDITION",
			"tag": "Verification-Result"
		},
		{
			"id": 9,
			"parent": 8,
			"text": "In addition , we provide evidence for a decrease in basal transcription activity in vitro . <S>",
			"relation": "ADDITION",
			"tag": "Verification-Result"
		},
		{
			"id": 10,
			"parent": 9,
			"text": "The latter defect may provide an explanation for many of the XP and CS symptoms that are difficult to rationalize based solely on an NER defect . <S>",
			"relation": "CAUSE-RESULT",
			"tag": "Verification-Result"
		},
		{
			"id": 11,
			"parent": 3,
			"text": "Thus , this work presents the first detailed analysis of a naturally occurring mutation in a basal transcription factor",
			"relation": "CONCLUSION",
			"tag": "Conclusion"
		},
		{
			"id": 12,
			"parent": 11,
			"text": "and supports the concept that the combined XP/CS clinical entity is actually the result of a combined transcription/repair deficiency . <S>",
			"relation": "ADDITION",
			"tag": "Conclusion"
		}
	]
}